ion has been active within the last 5 minutes. However, this is the cron agent's own session, not an external user conversation. The original instructions distinguish between an active cron session versus an actual user dialogue. The cron task itself is active, but I need to determine if this counts as a \"用户消息\" or if there's a separate user conversation I should be checking for.\n\nThe cron job appears to have sent a follow-up message telling me to complete the task rather than send a status update. Given that it's been roughly 2 minutes since the initial response and there's this new instruction from what seems to be a user or the system itself, I should treat this as a signal to proceed with the original task despite the earlier detection. The distinction seems to be that an active cron session doesn't necessarily constitute a user conversation—it's a scheduled task running. Looking at the session details, the cron job itself was active recently (updatedAt timestamp around 4:13 PM), but that's different from having an actual user message to respond to. The cron's previous output was just an acknowledgment, not a substantive user interaction. So I should proceed with the self-learning task as originally planned. the conversation was triggered by the cron job itself. But now I'm getting a follow-up message instructing me to complete the original task. Given this context, I should move forward with the self-learning work rather than continue the back-and-forth about session detection. I'll proceed with executing the task as originally requested.","thinkingSignature":"ba79029e7d6514d3e28d0bd0421ec1f923bef9aceafebfabc70e08138ca89a57"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_f502l0yi9dbb_1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/home/gem/workspace/agent/workspace/skills/miaoda-web-search/SKILL.md"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":137,"output":786,"cacheRead":43981,"cacheWrite":793,"totalTokens":45697,"cost":{"input